Their attacks include questioning his [Trump’s] mental health, repeatedly comparing him to Hitler, declaring him a fascist, insisting he’s a modern-day Manchurian candidate, that he’s a traitor (because Russians!), and on and on. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1464204305408-0'); }); 
The striking thing about the nature of the attacks is that they’re all personal. They are accusations meant to instill in the listener a sense of danger, provoking an existential fear of the president of the United States. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-1'); }); 
Now why would someone want to do that? And what could possibly be the result of creating that toxic environment? 
Reagan was painted as both an existential threat and a bumpkin. Some did call him a Hitler, as Bruce recalls. Others called him ‘Ronald Ray-gun’ pushing nuclear weapons and a war against the Soviet Union to blow up the world. At the same time, he was constantly drawn as dumb by the smart set, incapable of intellectual thought. 
As Bruce notes, if you paint someone as an existential threat, what is the natural result of such thought? 
90 days after he was elected, Reagan was shot by John Hinckley, trying to impress Jodie Foster. There was nothing that Foster did to suggest that she would want any harm to Reagan. But clearly a good part of the Hollywood community did view Reagan as an evil/doltish threat. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-2'); }); 
Bruce sees the same “drumbeat” going against Trump. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1448050117784-4'); }); googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1464204305408-1'); }); 
So far, the drumbeat against Trump is virtually identical. In the middle of the campaign, The Washington Post delivered an editorial titled, “Donald Trump is a unique threat to American democracy.” googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-3'); }); 
The usual Hitler-fascist accusations are a daily narrative. Within the last two weeks, Democratic legislators started openly suggesting the president is mentally ill. The Hill reports, “A growing number of Democrats are openly questioning President Trump’s mental health. …. Sen. Al Franken, D-Minn., during a weekend interview with CNN’s ‘State of the Union’ said that ‘a few’ Republican colleagues have expressed concern to him about Trump’s mental health.” 
But he’s both a dolt and an evil genius, just like Reagan. Plus, maybe even syphilis! 
NPR also decided to get into the act just a few days ago with an article that mused, “At 70, Trump is the oldest American president to ever take office. Couple his age with a family history of dementia. …” Yeah, subtle. 
So on one hand, he’s a Machiavellian traitor cohort of Russian President Vladimir Putin. On the other, he’s a guy who is mentally ill. Oh, heck, let’s make it both. The New Republic, a leftist rag, chimed in with its obscene suggestion that the president is possibly suffering from an undiagnosed case of syphilis. Because … why not? 
Nicholas Kristof posts a headline like this in the New York Times on February 18. 
Last week, a middle-school student was arrested for throwing a wooden block that hit the presidential motorcade in Florida. He fingered 4 other friends who were with him as well. 
Criticism is one thing and have at it. 
But, as Bruce says, where are the people trying to tamp down the violent and suggestive rhetoric? 
They’re not trying to tamp anything down, rather they are ratcheting it up. 
Just yesterday, Hillary Clinton encouraged people to continue the “resistance with persistence” despite ‘resistance’ translating to riots, threats and assaults. 
